                    <h2 class="post-title">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to &lt;i>Special Responsibilities: Global Problems and American Power&lt;/i> by Mlada Bukovansky, Ian Clark, Robyn Eckersley, Richard Price, Christian Reus-Smit, and Nicholas Wheeler" rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/special-responsibilities-global-problems-and-american-power-mlada-bukovansky-ian-clark-robyn-eckersley-richard-price-christian-reus-smit-and-nicholas-wheeler/">
                        <i>
                          Special Responsibilities: Global Problems and American Power
                        </i>
                         by Mlada Bukovansky, Ian Clark, Robyn Eckersley, Richard Price, Christian Reus-Smit, and Nicholas Wheeler
                      </a>
                    </h2>
                    <div class="meta">
                      <span class="meta-author">
                        <a rel="author" title="Posts by Stephen M. Walt" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/?p=6747#bio">
                          Stephen M. Walt
                        </a>
                         | 
	
                      </span>
                      <span class="meta-date">
                        
		January 7, 2014	
                      </span>
                    </div>
                    <p>
                      Claims for “special responsibilities” are sometimes made to rally domestic support for some costly international action, or to exempt a great power from norms that weaker states are expected to follow.
                    </p>
                    <p class="readmore">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to &lt;i>Special Responsibilities: Global Problems and American Power&lt;/i> by Mlada Bukovansky, Ian Clark, Robyn Eckersley, Richard Price, Christian Reus-Smit, and Nicholas Wheeler" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/special-responsibilities-global-problems-and-american-power-mlada-bukovansky-ian-clark-robyn-eckersley-richard-price-christian-reus-smit-and-nicholas-wheeler/" class="more-link">
                        Read More
                      </a>
                    </p>
                    <div style="clear:both;">
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div id="post-main-6763" class="post-6763 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-book-review category-issue-27-4">
                  <div class="entry clearfix">
                    <a title="Permanent Link to &lt;i>Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique&lt;/i> by Daniel J. Levine" rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/recovering-international-relations-the-promise-of-sustainable-critique-daniel-j-levine/">
                      <img title="&lt;i>Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique&lt;/i> by Daniel J. Levine" alt="&lt;i>Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique&lt;/i> by Daniel J. Levine" src="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/9780199916085_p0_v2_s260x420-150x150.jpg" class="thumbnail"/>
                    </a>
                    <h2 class="post-title">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to &lt;i>Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique&lt;/i> by Daniel J. Levine" rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/recovering-international-relations-the-promise-of-sustainable-critique-daniel-j-levine/">
                        <i>
                          Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique
                        </i>
                         by Daniel J. Levine
                      </a>
                    </h2>
                    <div class="meta">
                      <span class="meta-author">
                        <a rel="author" title="Posts by Richard Shapcott" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/?p=6763#bio">
                          Richard Shapcott
                        </a>
                         | 
	
                      </span>
                      <span class="meta-date">
                        
		January 7, 2014	
                      </span>
                    </div>
                    <p>
                      Daniel Levine’s goal is to “recover” IR’s original vocation, or calling, and to reinvigorate it via the idea of “sustainable critique”—a project inspired by the work of Theodor Adorno and the Frankfurt School.
                    </p>
                    <p class="readmore">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to &lt;i>Recovering International Relations: The Promise of Sustainable Critique&lt;/i> by Daniel J. Levine" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/recovering-international-relations-the-promise-of-sustainable-critique-daniel-j-levine/" class="more-link">
                        Read More
                      </a>
                    </p>
                    <div style="clear:both;">
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div id="post-main-6735" class="post-6735 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-article category-issue-27-4">
                  <div class="entry clearfix">
                    <a title="Permanent Link to On Rights to Land, Expulsions, and Corrective Justice" rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/on-rights-to-land-expulsions-and-corrective-justice/">
                    </a>
                    <h2 class="post-title">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to On Rights to Land, Expulsions, and Corrective Justice" rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/on-rights-to-land-expulsions-and-corrective-justice/">
                        
												On Rights to Land, Expulsions, and Corrective Justice
                      </a>
                    </h2>
                    <div class="meta">
                      <span class="meta-author">
                        <a rel="author" title="Posts by Margaret Moore" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/?p=6789">
                          Margaret Moore
                        </a>
                         | 
	
                      </span>
                      <span class="meta-date">
                        
		January 6, 2014	
                      </span>
                    </div>
                    <p>
                      This article examines the nature of the wrongs that are inflicted on individuals and groups who have been expelled from the land that they previously occupied, and asks what they might consequently be owed as a matter of corrective justice. I argue that there are three sorts of potential wrongs involved in such expulsions: being deprived of the moral right of occupancy; being denied collective self-determination; and having one’s property rights violated. 
                    </p>
                    <p class="readmore">
                      <a title="Permanent Link to On Rights to Land, Expulsions, and Corrective Justice" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2014/on-rights-to-land-expulsions-and-corrective-justice/" class="more-link">
                        Read More
                      </a>
                    </p>
                    <div style="clear:both;">
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="navigation clearfix">
                  <a href="http://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/page/2/?s=us">
                    Next Page »
                  </a>
                </div>
